---
import PageLayout from '../../../layouts/PageLayout.astro';
import Breadcrumbs from '../../../components/seo/Breadcrumbs.astro';
import BristolQuiz from '../../../components/tools/BristolQuiz';
import { articleSchema, breadcrumbSchema, faqSchema } from '../../../utils/schema';
import { getCanonicalUrl, SITE } from '../../../utils/seo';

const url = getCanonicalUrl(Astro.url.pathname);
const title = 'Bristol Stool Chart Quiz — Find Your Type in 30 Seconds';
const description = 'Free Bristol Stool Scale quiz. Answer 2–3 quick questions and find out which of the 7 Bristol types your stool is — with an explanation of what it means.';

const faqItems = [
  {
    question: 'What is the Bristol Stool Chart?',
    answer: 'The Bristol Stool Chart (or Bristol Stool Scale) is a clinical tool developed in 1997 at the Bristol Royal Infirmary that classifies stool into 7 types, from hard pellets (Type 1) to fully liquid (Type 7). Types 3 and 4 are considered the healthy range.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How accurate is this quiz?',
    answer: "The quiz uses the same classification criteria as clinical Bristol Stool Scale charts. It's accurate for identifying your Bristol type, but not a medical diagnostic tool — it tells you what type your stool is, not what's causing it. For persistent issues, see a clinician.",
  },
  {
    question: "What's a healthy Bristol type?",
    answer: 'Types 3 and 4 are considered the healthy range. Type 4 is often called the "gold standard" — smooth, soft, snake-like, and easy to pass. Occasional drift into other types is normal; it\'s the pattern over weeks that matters.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What should I do if my type is unhealthy?',
    answer: 'For Types 1–2 (constipation), focus on fiber, fluid, and movement. For Types 6–7 (diarrhea), prioritize hydration with electrolytes and avoid dietary triggers. For any concerning pattern lasting more than 2 weeks, or for any blood, mucus, unexplained weight loss, or severe pain, see a clinician.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Is this the same as an AI stool analysis?',
    answer: 'No — this quiz relies on your self-description. PoopCheck\'s AI does the analysis automatically from a photo, classifying Bristol type, color, and consistency in seconds, and tracks the pattern over time. The app is more accurate and much easier than describing stool with words.',
  },
];

const schema = [
  {
    '@context': 'https://schema.org',
    '@type': 'WebApplication',
    name: 'Bristol Stool Chart Quiz',
    description,
    url,
    applicationCategory: 'HealthApplication',
    operatingSystem: 'Web',
    offers: { '@type': 'Offer', price: '0', priceCurrency: 'USD' },
    publisher: { '@type': 'Organization', name: SITE.name, url: SITE.url },
  },
  articleSchema({
    title,
    description,
    url,
    datePublished: '2026-04-20T00:00:00Z',
    dateModified: '2026-04-20T00:00:00Z',
    author: 'PoopCheck Team',
    medical: true,
  }),
  breadcrumbSchema([
    { name: 'Home', url: `${SITE.url}/` },
    { name: 'Tools', url: `${SITE.url}/tools/` },
    { name: 'Bristol Stool Chart Quiz', url },
  ]),
  faqSchema(faqItems),
];
---

<PageLayout seo={{ title, description, type: 'article' }} schema={schema}>
  <article class="py-12 md:py-20">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-5">

      <div class="mb-8">
        <Breadcrumbs
          items={[
            { label: 'Tools', href: '/tools/' },
            { label: 'Bristol Stool Chart Quiz', href: Astro.url.pathname },
          ]}
        />
      </div>

      <header class="mb-10 text-center">
        <div class="inline-block px-3 py-1 rounded-full text-xs font-semibold bg-[var(--color-accent)]/10 text-[var(--color-accent)] mb-4">
          Free Tool
        </div>
        <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl lg:text-5xl font-bold leading-tight">
          Bristol Stool Chart Quiz
        </h1>
        <p class="mt-4 text-lg text-[var(--color-text-muted)] leading-relaxed max-w-2xl mx-auto">
          Answer 2–3 quick questions and find out which of the 7 Bristol Stool Scale types your stool is — with an explanation of what it means and how to shift toward the healthy range.
        </p>
      </header>

      {/* The quiz (React island) */}
      <BristolQuiz client:load />

      {/* SEO content below the fold */}
      <div class="prose prose-invert prose-lg max-w-none mt-16
        prose-headings:font-bold prose-headings:text-[var(--color-text)]
        prose-h2:text-2xl prose-h2:mt-12 prose-h2:mb-4
        prose-h3:text-xl prose-h3:mt-8 prose-h3:mb-3
        prose-p:text-[var(--color-text-muted)] prose-p:leading-relaxed
        prose-a:text-[var(--color-accent)] prose-a:no-underline hover:prose-a:underline
        prose-strong:text-[var(--color-text)]
        prose-li:text-[var(--color-text-muted)]
      ">

        <h2>How this quiz works</h2>
        <p>
          The Bristol Stool Scale is a widely-used clinical tool for classifying
          stool consistency. It maps stool into seven distinct types based on
          shape and texture:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Types 1–2:</strong> Hard, separate lumps — constipation territory.</li>
          <li><strong>Types 3–4:</strong> Smooth and well-formed — the healthy range.</li>
          <li><strong>Types 5–7:</strong> Soft, mushy, or liquid — loose-to-diarrhea range.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Our quiz narrows down your type with 2–3 simple questions based on
          appearance (separate pieces vs connected shape), surface (lumpy vs
          cracked vs smooth), and consistency (solid vs mushy vs liquid). The
          logic mirrors how clinicians quickly classify stool using the chart.
        </p>

        <h2>What your Bristol type tells you</h2>
        <p>
          Your Bristol type is a direct readout of colon transit time and water
          absorption. Hard types (1–2) mean stool sat too long in the colon and
          too much water was reabsorbed. Liquid types (6–7) mean stool moved too
          fast for the colon to absorb water at all. Types 3–4 hit the balance.
        </p>
        <p>
          No single day of stool defines your gut health. The pattern over weeks
          does. That's why we built PoopCheck: the app automatically classifies
          Bristol type, color, and consistency from a photo — so tracking is
          effortless enough to actually do daily, and the pattern becomes
          visible.
        </p>

        <h2>Common questions</h2>
        {faqItems.map((f) => (
          <>
            <h3>{f.question}</h3>
            <p>{f.answer}</p>
          </>
        ))}

        <h2>Dig deeper</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><a href="/bristol/">The complete Bristol Stool Scale guide</a> — all 7 types with detailed breakdowns</li>
          <li><a href="/poopcheck-blog/fiber-and-stool-consistency/">Fiber and stool consistency</a> — how diet shifts your Bristol type</li>
          <li><a href="/poopcheck-blog/how-often-should-you-poop-3-shocking-facts-you-need-to-know/">How often should you poop?</a> — frequency vs consistency</li>
          <li><a href="/poopcheck-blog/how-to-improve-gut-health/">10 evidence-based ways to improve gut health</a></li>
        </ul>

        <p class="text-xs">
          Disclaimer: This quiz provides informational classification based on the
          Bristol Stool Scale. It is not medical advice and does not diagnose any
          condition. If you're experiencing persistent changes in bowel habits,
          blood in stool, unexplained weight loss, or severe pain, see a
          qualified healthcare provider.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
</PageLayout>
